<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/technology <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/technology" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 28 日星期五 03:13:27 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Intel Returns to Profit as PC Rebound Lifts Chip Demand]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>连续两个季度创纪录亏损后，芯片制造商的盈利令华尔街大吃一惊<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091470"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824336?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英特尔预计本季度营收为 129 亿至 139 亿美元，高于华尔街的预期。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jordi Boixareu/ZUMA Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091470"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/asa-fitch" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿萨·菲奇</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日晚上 7:23（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-intl-q2-earnings-report-2023-13010e83"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/INTC" class="company-name">英特尔</a>股价周四飙升， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lenovo-ceo-expects-global-pc-sales-turnaround-by-end-2023-efcddf50?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">个人电脑市场的复苏</a>帮助其从两个季度创纪录的亏损中反弹，并且预测人工智能繁荣将带来新的需求。</p><p> 15 亿美元的利润超出了分析师对再次亏损的预期。此前，英特尔公布上一季度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-corp-intc-q1-earnings-report-2023-91aab8b3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">亏损 27.6 亿美元</a>，这是这家传奇芯片制造商有史以来最严重的亏损。</p><p>首席执行官帕特·基辛格 (Pat Gelsinger) 表示，该公司正在实施两年多前接掌公司时制定的雄心勃勃的转型计划。他表示，对人工智能的需求将推动近几个季度萎靡不振的个人电脑和数据中心部门的发展。</p><p>英特尔第二季度营收较上一季度有所增长，达到129亿美元，超出了华尔街的预期。收入比去年同期下降 15%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=419229E6-2C0B-46A8-8C1C-60F5B5BFD5BE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fintel-intl-q2-earnings-report-2023-13010e83&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">去年，AMD 的市值超过了英特尔，部分原因在于对芯片设计的昂贵押注。 《华尔街日报》的阿萨·菲奇 (Asa Fitch) 解释了各公司为争夺计算机大脑而展开的斗争。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>公布业绩后，英特尔股价在盘后交易中上涨 8%。</p><p>该公司预计本季度营收为 129 亿至 139 亿美元，高于华尔街的预期。</p><p>英特尔因个人电脑销量急剧下降而受到打击，而个人电脑占其收入的很大一部分。在大流行最严重的时期，人们争先恐后地购买电子产品以便在家工作和学习，销售量蓬勃发展。去年，情况发生了逆转，人们恢复了旧习惯，导致制造商货架上的芯片过剩。</p><p>近几个月来，随着制造商耗尽芯片库存并发出新订单，个人电脑市场一直显示出复苏的迹象。根据国际数据公司 (International Data Corp.) 的数据，第二季度个人电脑出货量下降了 13.4%，比第一季度 29% 的跌幅更为温和。</p><p>基辛格在接受采访时表示，该公司相信本季度其个人电脑芯片市场份额有所增加，而且库存状况也有所改善。</p><p> “个人电脑作为一个品类现在又恢复健康了，”他说。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>英特尔表示，第二季度 PC 芯片部门的销售额下降了 12%。但第一季度该部门的销售额为 68 亿美元，超过了 58 亿美元。</p><p>基辛格表示，随着人工智能的兴趣从明年开始推动个人电脑的销售，该部门的未来可能会更加光明，因为针对人工智能而优化的新一代个人电脑芯片支持实时语言翻译和生产力软件插件等工具。</p><p>芯片制造商已经开始从人们对所谓的生成式人工智能系统的兴趣激增中获利，这种系统可以在最少的提示下生成复杂的文本和图像。</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="">Nvidia</a><span class="company-name-type">是</span>一家生产用于创建此类系统的芯片的公司，其强劲的收入预测超出了分析师的预期，其估值飙升至超过 1 万亿美元。<p></p><p>大型科技公司正在大力投资人工智能能力及其背后的芯片。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">微软</a>周二报告销售增长缓慢，但强调人工智能是其业务发展的驱动力。谷歌的母公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="">Alphabet</a>本周也公布了业绩<span class="company-name-type">，该</span>公司正在向人工智能系统投入资金。</p><p>英特尔的中央处理器广泛应用于人工智能计算，并提供图形处理单元和其他专业人工智能芯片。基辛格表示，英特尔的 AI 加速器芯片订单量超过 10 亿美元。</p><p>不过，他表示，目前大型数据中心运营商正在将初始投资重点放在人工智能芯片上</p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVDA" class="company-name">英伟达</a>专门从事.<p></p><p>基辛格表示：“我们确实认为这会在短期内抑制 CPU 需求。”他补充说，他预计随着时间的推移，采购将重新转向 CPU，从而为英特尔创造机会。</p><p>除了人工智能挑战之外，英特尔还面临着来自长期竞争对手 Advanced Micro Devices 的数据输入芯片日益激烈的竞争。它推迟了今年年初上市的最先进的数据中心处理器的推出。</p><p>该公司数据中心和人工智能部门的销售额第二季度下降了 15%，至 40 亿美元。</p><p>在市场困境中，基辛格宣布裁员，并承诺今年削减成本 30 亿美元，并在 2025 年底之前每年削减成本至 100 亿美元。</p><p>与此同时，这位首席执行官正试图扭转局面，需要对新的芯片制造工厂进行巨额投资，并力争在用最小的晶体管制造计算速度最快的芯片方面赶上韩国和台湾的竞争对手。</p><p>该公司正在根据去年通过的 530 亿美元 CHIPS 法案寻求政府拨款，以资助其在美国的雄心壮志。该公司已提交了扩建亚利桑那州生产设施的资金申请，并计划今年再提交三项提案。四分之一，基辛格说。</p><p>此次扭亏为盈的核心是一项为他人代工生产筹码的新业务。尽管该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-gelsinger-nvidia-turnaround-30febac6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">正在与台湾联发科和美国硬盘制造商希捷合作，但所谓的代工业务在头两年仍难以赢得</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TW/XTAI/2454" class="company-name">高通</a>和英<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/STX" class="">伟达</a>等大客户<span class="company-name-type">。</span>该公司本周表示，它签署了一项协议，使用其最先进的芯片制造技术为电信设备制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ERIC" class="company-name">爱立信</a>制造芯片。</p><p>写信给 Asa Fitch： <a href="mailto:asa.fitch@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">asa.fitch@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/d90969df-db3f-4890-9f4e-2892f502493a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 23:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-intl-q2-earnings-report-2023-13010e83</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/intel-intl-q2-earnings-report-2023-13010e83<author><![CDATA[Asa Fitch]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>公司收益</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>木制家具</category><category>消费品</category><category>家具</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>盈利惊喜</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>英伟达</category><category>NVDA</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>字母 C1A</category><category>谷歌</category><category>英特尔</category><category>国际贸易中心</category><category>帕特·基辛格</category><category>财务绩效</category><category>收益</category><category>盈利惊喜</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>半导体</category><category>木制家具</category><category>消费品</category><category>家具</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>集成电路</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Economic Growth Accelerates]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>上季度经济增长2.4%，表明美国正在摆脱衰退<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087898"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="581" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824191?width=860&amp;height=581" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">消费者支出一直在推动美国经济。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087898"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-chaney-cambon" itemprop="url" rel="author">莎拉·钱尼·坎本</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/christian-robles" itemprop="url" rel="author">克里斯蒂安·罗伯斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日下午 5:20（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尽管美联储<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将利率推</a>至二十年来的高位，但今年春季更快的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-27-2023?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济增长</a>提高了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/could-a-recession-still-be-years-away-soft-landing-could-deliver-another-extended-economic-cycle-e7e2c4ee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">疫情后经济扩张时间更长</a>的前景。</p><p>美国商务部周四表示，经季节性因素和通胀因素调整后，第二季度<a href="https://www.bea.gov/sites/default/files/2023-07/gdp2q23_adv.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">国内</a>生产总值年增长率为 2.4%。这比经济学家预期的要快，并且高于今年前三个月 2% 的增长率。</p><p>第二季度消费者支出降温，但增长足以推动整体增长，同时商业投资也大幅增强。这些因素结合在一起，违背了经济学家此前的预期，即由于利率上升，经济衰退将在今年年中开始。</p><p>随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通胀从历史高位回落</a>且劳动力市场依然强劲，稳健的增长增加了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-inflation-goes-down-soft-landing-odds-improve-5166e6af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">软着陆</a>的前景——即通胀在不出现衰退的情况下恢复到接近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/news-explainers/the-feds-2-inflation-target-explained/F0A8BD11-B153-4E7E-8454-B5C1C8CD12BD?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美联储 2% 的目标</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="850" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825207?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> AC Cutts &amp; Associates 首席经济学家艾米·克鲁斯·卡茨 (Amy Crews Cutts) 在数据发布前表示：“我们已经扭转了这里的风险，不再过度关注衰退，而是在衰退与非衰退之间保持平衡。”</p><p>美国股指周四走低。道琼斯工业平均指数下跌 237.40 点，跌幅 0.67%。更广泛的标准普尔 500 指数下跌 0.64%，以科技股为主的纳斯达克指数下跌 0.55%。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>美联储周三将基准利率上调0.25个百分点，至5.25%至5.5%之间，创22年来新高。美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔表示，是否进一步加息将取决于通胀和经济活动放缓是否符合官员的预测。</p><p>他在新闻发布会上表示：“我们必须做好跟踪数据的准备，考虑到我们已经取得的进展，我们可以在事态的发展过程中保持一点耐心和决心。”</p><p>继 2022 年初出现温和收缩后，过去一年经济增长速度超过 2%。经济增长与疫情爆发前十年的增速大致一致。</p><h3>消费者支出降温，仍推动增长</h3><p>第二季度消费者支出年增长率为1.6%，低于第一季度的4.2%。家庭支出占经济活动的大部分，占GDP增长总量的近一半。</p><p>经济放缓主要反映了美国人在今年年初抢购汽车后大件商品的购买降温，因为这些汽车流回了经销店。</p><p> Visa 首席财务官 Vasant Prabhu 周二表示，近几个月消费者支出下降也反映出汽油价格下降。根据能源数据提供商 OPIS 的数据，每加仑普通汽油的平均价格比去年同期下降了约 60 美分。普拉布表示，除此之外，支出基本保持一致。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6B575582-5695-4577-8048-E886C31EFE0B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fus-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔周三表示，央行将把基准利率提高四分之一个百分点，使美国利率升至22年来的最高点。照片：内森·霍华德/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>他表示，“自三月份以来，从富裕到低消费的消费者支出保持稳定”。 “我们的数据没有表明消费者群体的行为发生任何变化。”</p><p>美国人正受益于强劲的劳动力市场，工资涨幅<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pay-raises-are-finally-beating-inflation-after-two-years-of-falling-behind-3e89bc2d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近超过了降温的通胀</a>。美国劳工部周四表示，作为裁员指标的初请失业金人数上周减少了 7,000 人，至经季节性调整后的 221,000 人。这是历史最低水平，基本上与 2019 年劳动力市场也强劲时的平均水平相符。</p><p>格斯·阿亚拉，</p>一位 73 岁的退休银行家正在挥霍一些大笔采购，同时减少一些日常用品的购买。这位亚利桑那州埃尔米拉日市的居民计划在今年晚些时候购买一辆混合动力汽车，并且可能会为这辆车提供融资，而不是支付现金。他和妻子的储蓄缓冲正在帮助支付妻子即将前往冰岛的旅行费用。<p></p><p> “我们想把钱花在对我们有利、让我们享受生活的事情上，”阿亚拉说。</p><p>阿亚拉改变了一些消费习惯以应对通货膨胀加剧。今年早些时候，他喜欢的一袋 12 盎司咖啡品牌的价格从去年的 9 美元飙升至 12 美元，今年早些时候，他转而购买更便宜的咖啡品牌 Seattle&#39;s Best。阿亚拉仍然需要每天喝咖啡，他一边喝着早晨的咖啡一边说道。</p><h3>今年春天商业投资猛增</h3><p>第二季度商业投资年率增长7.7%，较一季度的0.6%大幅增长。</p><p>尽管利率上升，但一些长期力量正在帮助刺激投资。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-factory-building-boom-93dfb8f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">联邦政府在芯片制造工厂和电动汽车工厂方面的支出激增</a>，抵消了其他一些削减。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1300" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824784?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>第二季度企业设备支出出现反弹，这主要是由于供应链陷入混乱而对飞机和汽车的投资。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/RF" class="">Regions Financial</a>首席经济学家理查德·穆迪 (Richard F. Moody) 在一份报告中表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>随着这一过程的结束，设备和机械支出可能会再次减弱。</p><p>第二季度净贸易增长略有下降，反映出<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球经济低迷</a>。住宅投资连续第九个季度下降。最近住宅投资的下降反映出抵押贷款利率上升导致房地产市场紧张。</p><p>尽管如此，二手房长期短缺仍有助于支持新建筑。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/housings-recession-already-happened-26bbb505?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">房地产市场低迷</a>最严重的时期可能已经过去，这意味着未来几个月住宅投资可能会增长。</p><h3>对经济放缓的担忧依然存在</h3><p>今年晚些时候消费者和企业的支出是否会保持同样的速度尚不清楚。</p><p>高利率将持续存在，导致车辆、电器、工厂机器和建筑项目的借贷成本更高。此外，学生贷款偿还将于今年晚些时候恢复，这对一些消费者来说是另一个阻力。</p><p> Ben &amp; Jerry&#39;s 冰淇淋、Hellmann&#39;s 蛋黄酱和 Dove 肥皂的制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UL" class="company-name">联合利华 (Unilever)</a>的首席财务官表示，北美消费者在花掉疫情期间积累的超额积蓄时，“ <a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://economics.cmail19.com/t/d-l-vykurjl-jitttilkij-q/__;!!F0Stn7g!DV3eXrYbx9JhECsWYg4fdcj9hFK4Boi0MRqviS41tozzX0mJOty4bazHM82zDFiVzUFJiz8ShIuC9w9fmOmO7AI$" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">开始表现出谨慎的迹象</a>”。</p><p> “我们仍然认为有可能出现温和的衰退，”首席财务官格雷姆·皮特凯斯利(Graeme Pitkethly)表示。</p><p>伊利诺伊州奥罗拉地区的 CertaPro Painters 总经理杰西·罗德里格斯 (Jesse Rodriguez) 表示，与一年前相比，客户对住宅油漆估价的请求减少了约 30%。</p><p>需求回落是在经历了两年的大流行中断之后发生的。 2021年，油漆公司招工速度不够快。去年，该公司因供应链混乱而陷入困境，限制了涂料的供应。</p><p> “我原本希望 23 年会是正常的一年，但事实证明并非如此，”罗德里格斯说。</p><p>罗德里格斯表示，随着业务放缓，该公司最近削减了营销费用，包括向潜在客户直邮传单的费用。</p><h3>长期前景乐观</h3><p>许多经济学家仍然预计经济增长将在今年晚些时候和 2024 年放缓，但他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-are-cutting-back-their-recession-expectations-74118938?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正在消除对经济衰退的担忧</a>。</p><p>世界大型企业联合会本周表示，7 月份美国消费者信心继续改善，许多美国人对未来表示更加乐观。消费者对经济衰退的担忧减少。</p><p>小企业对经济的感受也有所好转。商业辅导和同行咨询公司伟事达 (Vistage Worldwide) 的数据显示，7 月，37% 的小企业表示，他们认为未来 12 个月经济将恶化，这是自 2022 年 2 月以来的最佳记录。</p><p> <a href="https://www.imf.org/en/Publications/WEO/Issues/2023/07/10/world-economic-outlook-update-july-2023" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">国际货币基金组织周二表示</a>，今年美国和全球的经济增长可能会强于此前的估计。前景的改善反映了劳动力市场的强劲、旅游业等服务业支出的强劲以及金融稳定风险的降低。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——尼克·蒂米罗斯对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Sarah Chaney Cambon <a href="mailto:sarah.chaney@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(sarah.chaney@wsj.com)</a>和 Christian Robles ( <a href="mailto:christian.robles@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">christian.robles@wsj.com</a> ) </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/b53b02aa-8e94-4e61-9c59-71310c5dc08d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 21:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437<author><![CDATA[Sarah Chaney CambonChristian Robles]]></author><category>通货膨胀</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>银行业</category><category>中央银行业务</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>消费者支出数据</category><category>货币政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>消费者支出/预算</category><category>通货膨胀</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>瓦桑帕布</category><category>格雷姆·皮特凯斯利</category><category>艾米·克鲁斯·卡茨</category><category>杰罗姆·鲍威尔</category><category>格斯·阿亚拉</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>消费者支出数字</category><category>货币政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>消费支出</category><category>预算编制</category><category>银行业</category><category>中央银行</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Sequoia Capital Slashes Crypto Fund]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在做出一系列有争议的决定后，该品牌受到了密切关注<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091627"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="557" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825203?width=860&amp;height=557" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">通过削减基金规模，红杉资本降低了投资者所需的承诺资本金额。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔什·埃德尔森/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091627"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/berber-jin" itemprop="url" rel="author">柏柏尔·金</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日下午 4:59 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sequoia-capital-slashes-crypto-fund-as-it-downsizes-amid-startup-crunch-f396bb0b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>红杉资本削减了包括其加密货币基金在内的两只主要风险基金的规模，这是这家传奇风险投资公司在初创企业普遍低迷时期大幅缩减规模的一部分。</p><p>据知情人士透露，红杉资本将其加密货币基金规模从 5.85 亿美元削减至 2 亿美元。知情人士称，该公司还将投资其他风险基金的所谓生态系统基金的规模从 9 亿美元削减至 4.5 亿美元。</p><p>红杉资本在三月份告诉基金投资者，它决定减少基金规模，以更好地反映市场变化。例如，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-crisis-a-timeline-of-key-events-11675519887?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">行业崩溃</a>消除了支持大公司的机会之后，加密货币基金将更多地关注于支持年轻的初创公司。</p><p>通过削减基金规模，红杉正在降低投资者（即有限合伙人）所需的承诺资本金额，这些投资者已经看到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venture-fund-returns-suffer-amid-lower-startup-values-15dc0130?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">风险基金的回报率较低</a>，并准备迎接进一步的降价。</p><p>这些变化表明，在近年来创业行业最艰难的几年之一中，风险投资公司正在做出艰难的削减。他们正试图消除历史性创业热潮所特有的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venture-firms-scale-back-megafunds-in-strategy-shift-17807564?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">惊人扩张</a>和自由支出，随着交易放缓和基金<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venture-fundraising-hits-nine-year-low-c2b4774?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">难以筹集更多现金</a>，这种做法不再有意义。</p><p>红杉资本在花费数月时间加大对加密货币的投资后，于 2022 年 2 月宣布了这两只基金，作为雄心勃勃的公司重组的一部分。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-rout-deflates-some-web3-startups-buoyed-by-push-into-digital-tokens-11657359180?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">此后，加密货币崩盘已经消灭了许多区块链初创公司的收入</a>。</p><p>红杉资本长期以来被视为硅谷顶级风险投资公司，以适应科技投资市场的变化并确保其领先于竞争对手而闻名。但该公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venture-powerhouse-sequoia-capital-set-to-name-new-leader-sources-say-11649092462?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在新领导层的领导下</a>遭遇了一系列挫折，多年来首次使其品牌面临严重压力。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>该公司因向去年倒闭的加密货币交易所 FTX 投资 1.5 亿美元而备受<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/silicon-valley-poured-money-into-ftx-with-few-strings-attached-11668103682?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">瞩目</a>。据《华尔街日报》报道，红杉资本<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sequoia-capital-apologizes-to-limited-partners-for-ftx-investment-11669144914?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">罕见地就此次投资向投资者道歉</a>。</p><p>红杉资本还因其在 2021 年底做出的不合时宜的决定而受到投资者的批评，该决定推出了一个新的基金结构，允许其持有公开股票而不是退出这些头寸。红杉当时表示，新方法将使其能够获得更多利润，但去年科技市场崩溃后，该公司却遭受了数十亿美元的账面损失，削弱了其回报率，令投资者感到沮丧。</p><p>六月份，红杉资本将其美国和欧洲业务<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sequoia-made-a-fortune-investing-in-the-u-s-and-china-then-it-had-to-pick-one-f13e7b91?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与利润丰厚的中国业务</a>分开，此前双方的合作关系受到了立法者和白宫越来越严格的审查。红杉资本最成功的早期投资者之一迈克尔·莫里茨 (Michael Moritz) 在该公司工作近 40 年后于本月早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sequoia-partner-michael-moritz-to-leave-venture-firm-after-38-years-587219fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">辞职</a>。</p><p>写信给 Berber Jin，邮箱为<a href="mailto:berber.jin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">berber.jin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 20:59:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sequoia-capital-slashes-crypto-fund-as-it-downsizes-amid-startup-crunch-f396bb0b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/sequoia-capital-slashes-crypto-fund-as-it-downsizes-amid-startup-crunch-f396bb0b<author><![CDATA[Berber Jin]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>私人产权</category><category>另类投资</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟货币/加密货币</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>企业家/初创公司</category><category>中小型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>红杉资本</category><category>SEQCAP.XX</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业家</category><category>初创公司</category><category>小的</category><category>中型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>信托</category><category>资金</category><category>金融工具</category><category>私人产权</category><category>另类投资</category><category>银行业</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category><category>金融科技</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>技术</category><category>虚拟货币</category><category>加密货币</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Does Facebook Polarize Users? Meta Disagrees With Partners Over Research Conclusions]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公司和研究人员在如何解释 2020 年总统选举研究结果方面存在分歧<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001090980"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824980?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Meta 高管尼克·克莱格 (Nick Clegg) 表示，这些研究推翻了有关该公司算法“为人们提供导致他们分裂的内容”的说法。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：kenzo tribouillard/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001090980"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jeff-horwitz" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰夫·霍维茨</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日下午 3:53 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-facebook-polarize-users-meta-disagrees-with-partners-over-research-conclusions-24fde67a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>和一群学者就社交媒体对政治的影响进行了多年的研究合作，但在结果公布之前就陷入了对结论的分歧。</p><p>这项研究工作的四篇同行评审论文于周四在《科学》和《自然》杂志上发表，预计将有更多基于 Meta 向独立研究人员提供的数据的论文的开始。</p><p>该研究考察了 Meta 的 Facebook 部门在 2020 年大选期间在政治中的作用，并分析了该平台是否<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-algorithm-change-zuckerberg-11631654215?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在两极分化中发挥作用</a>等问题。 Meta 长期以来一直对这些人的说法提出异议，其中包括一些自己的研究人员， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebook-knows-it-encourages-division-top-executives-nixed-solutions-11590507499?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">他们表示，Meta 加剧了分歧，</a>部分原因是它过滤人们看到的信息的方式。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>前四篇文章涵盖的研究有不同的侧重点。他们广泛地展示了 Facebook 对用户在该平台上消费的信息的影响力，但部分表示，尚不清楚此类内容会影响他们的政治观点和行为。</p><p> Meta 的一份被禁止的声明表示，这些研究驳斥了有关其平台在用户两极分化和煽动政治言论方面发挥核心作用的指控。这促使该公司的学术合作伙伴、《科学》杂志的官员和一名负责监督研究工作的独立观察员表示，Meta 夸大或错误描述了一些研究结果。</p><p> Meta 表示，它对《科学》杂志印刷版的研究结果标题“连线到分裂”提出了质疑，称该标题错误地描述了这项工作。该出版物的代表表示，Meta 和外部研究人员要求在标题中添加问号以反映不确定性，但该出版物认为其对研究的介绍是公平的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=37245C31-BAF7-4987-B2C1-BA54167C5088&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdoes-facebook-polarize-users-meta-disagrees-with-partners-over-research-conclusions-24fde67a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Facebook 母公司 Meta 推出了 Threads，这是一款独立的微博应用程序，可与埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 的 Twitter 相媲美。 Meta 首席执行官马克·扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg) 表示，该应用程序在推出后 7 小时内就获得了 1000 万注册用户。照片：Yui Mok/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>一篇论文利用 2020 年美国大选前后几个月收集的数据发现，Facebook 页面和群组在该平台上的美国保守派中传播虚假新闻故事方面发挥了巨大作用。</p><p>其他研究发现，当研究人员尝试改变 Facebook 向用户发送帖子的方式时，用户的政治观点或行为并没有明显的影响。这些实验包括暂时限制用户提要中的转发内容（这些内容往往比 Facebook 算法推荐的内容更具政治性），并暂时按时间顺序而不是 Facebook 通常使用的算法确定的顺序显示用户帖子。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Meta 表示，没有其他科技公司向研究人员提供类似的数据访问权限，并且这些研究补充了越来越多的研究，驳斥了“仅 Meta 平台的关键功能”会导致有害两极分化的观点。该声明来自 Nick Clegg 的博客文章，</p> Meta 的全球事务总裁表示，该公司准备与调查结果一起发布。<p></p><p>克莱格写道，虽然这项研究并不能解决有关社交媒体和民主的所有争论，但周四发表的论文驳斥了该公司的算法“为人们提供导致他们分裂的内容”的说法。</p><p> Meta 声明中对论文的描述引发了分歧。</p><p>学术带头人纽约大学教授Joshua Tucker和德克萨斯大学奥斯汀分校教授Talia Stroud，</p>表示，虽然研究表明简单的算法调整并没有减少测试对象的两极分化，但这些论文包含警告和潜在解释，说明为什么在 2020 年选举的最后几个月进行的这种有限的改变不会改变用户的整体前景关于政治。<p></p><p> “这些论文的结论并不支持所有这些陈述，”斯特劳德说。克莱格的评论“不是我们会发表的声明”。</p><p>负责《科学》研究结果传播的梅根·费兰 (Meagan Phelan) 表示，本周早些时候，《科学》杂志警告 Meta，它将公开质疑一项主张，即已发表的研究应该被解读为在很大程度上免除了 Meta 在社会分歧中所扮演的重要角色。</p><p>根据她与《华尔街日报》分享的消息摘录，费兰周一对 Meta 的通讯团队表示：“研究结果表明，Meta 算法是导致人们分裂的重要因素。”她补充说，其中一项研究发现，“与自由派相比，政治保守派用户的新闻来源更加孤立，部分是由算法过程驱动的，在 Facebook 的页面和群组上尤其明显。”</p><p>作为回应，Meta 稍微改变了克莱格博客文章的措辞，但坚持其对研究结果的总体描述，称对研究解释的分歧是正常的。</p><p>在一次简短的采访中，《科学》编辑霍尔顿·索普称梅塔对克莱格声明的修改无关紧要。</p><p>威斯康星大学麦迪逊分校新闻学院的政治学家迈克尔·瓦格纳（Michael Wagner）表示：“科学有权利提出不同意见。”他被 Meta 和外部研究人员联合选为独立报告员，负责记录合作研究过程并评估其独立性和严谨性。</p><p>瓦格纳和其他熟悉这项研究的人表示，他们预计会发表更多论文，以找出人们对 Meta 平台如何塑造政治话语的担忧的重要原因。</p><p>瓦格纳表示，Meta 花费了超过 2000 万美元来促进这项研究，其工作人员与研究人员合作，但同意不控制他们的言论。研究人员的工作资金来自其他来源。</p><p>瓦格纳说：“梅塔表现出了对严格社会科学研究的坚定承诺。”但他表示，Meta“以影响研究人员整体独立性的方式设定议程”，例如通过工作流程决策。</p><p>专注于两极分化问题的前 Meta 数据科学家 Ravi Iyer 表示，过去的 Meta 研究还发现证据表明 Facebook 的机制有时偏向煽动性内容和冲突。</p><p> “我对所有参与人员的努力表示赞赏，但重要的是要将这些实验与 Meta 所做的其他数十项关于转发影响的类似研究结合起来，”现任南加州大学技术心理学研究所负责人的 Iyer 说道。在采访中说道。</p><p>写信给 Jeff Horwitz： <a href="mailto:jeff.horwitz@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jeff.horwitz@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 19:53:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-facebook-polarize-users-meta-disagrees-with-partners-over-research-conclusions-24fde67a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-facebook-polarize-users-meta-disagrees-with-partners-over-research-conclusions-24fde67a<author><![CDATA[Jeff Horwitz]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>元平台</category><category>梅塔</category><category>约书亚·塔克</category><category>塔利亚·斯特劳德</category><category>霍顿·索普</category><category>迈克尔·瓦格纳</category><category>拉维·耶尔</category><category>尼克·克莱格</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Mark Zuckerberg Could Be Held in Contempt of Congress: What to Know]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>众议院共和党人威胁要援引 Meta 首席执行官的话说，因为他们未能提供足够的文件来回应传票<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088343"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824019?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Meta Platforms 首席执行官马克·扎克伯格表示，其内容审核决策是独立的，与政治无关。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·保罗·莫里斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088343"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-tracy" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·特雷西</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日下午 1:27（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-zuckerberg-could-be-held-in-contempt-of-congress-what-to-know-e4027c45"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>共和党领导的众议院司法委员会周四威胁要进行投票，决定是否建议以藐视国会的罪名拘留<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">马克·扎克伯格</a>，除非他交出公司内部文件，这是关于政府官员与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-to-decide-if-u-s-government-improperly-censored-social-media-users-2686fed0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">社会</a>之间正确关系的长期辩论的一部分。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-to-decide-if-u-s-government-improperly-censored-social-media-users-2686fed0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">媒体公司</a>。</p><p>共和党人表示，Meta 和其他社交媒体公司正在审查保守派观点，有时是迫于政府压力。民主党人表示，政府必须与这些公司合作，应对选举操纵和其他威胁。这种紧张局势已经引发了一场<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-rules-biden-administration-likely-trampled-on-free-speech-on-social-media-29334362?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">法庭斗争</a>，有可能颠覆政府和社交媒体公司应对网络威胁的方式。 Facebook 和 Instagram 的所有者 Meta 现在发现自己成为这场争论的前沿和中心。</p><p>周四下午，众议员吉姆·乔丹（俄亥俄州共和党）在一条推文中表示，投票已被取消，因为 Meta 已开始制作文件。 “需要明确的是，蔑视仍然存在，如果 Facebook 未能全面合作，将会使用蔑视，”他说。</p><p>以下是您需要了解的信息：</p><h3>我们是怎么来到这里的？</h3><p>司法委员会主席乔丹去年年底询问 Meta <strong>&nbsp;</strong>移交有关其内容审核决策的内部文件——通常<strong>&nbsp;</strong>关于是否禁止账户或压制帖子的争议性呼吁。该小组于二月份发出了索取这些文件的传票。</p><p> Meta 周三表示，它已“交付了超过 53,000 页的内部和外部文件，并让近十几名现任和前任员工可以讨论外部和内部事务，其中包括本周安排的一些文件。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmark-zuckerberg-could-be-held-in-contempt-of-congress-what-to-know-e4027c45&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Twitter 所有者埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 和 Meta 首席执行官马克·扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg) 已同意进行笼式比赛。肢体冲突可能是第一次，但《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩在动作玩偶的帮助下解释了为什么这场科技斗殴实际上就像过去的硅谷争吵一样。照片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>它在一份声明中补充道：“几个月来，Meta 一直真诚地满足该委员会对信息的广泛要求......Meta 将继续遵守委员会的真诚要求，就像我们迄今为止所做的那样。”</p><p>但共和党人表示，该公司一直保留 Meta 员工之间关于如何应对政府要求其删除或压制某些内容的内部沟通。乔丹说，该公司周四开始移交其中一些文件。</p><h3>更广泛的背景是什么？</h3><p>近年来，一些政府机构与 Facebook、Twitter 和其他社交媒体平台开通了正式的沟通渠道。联邦官员可以标记感知到的威胁，例如包含有关选举或疫苗的虚假信息的帖子。就平台而言，有时会要求政府官员提供有关如何判断内容是否虚假或危险的指导。</p><p>共和党人认为这些互动的滥用时机已经成熟。他们认为，政府官员依靠这些公司来审查辩论，侵犯了美国人尤其是保守派的言论自由。</p><p>民主党人认为社交媒体公司在打击仇恨言论和他们认为的有害内容方面过于松懈。民主党人也倾向于更支持政府与社交媒体公司协调应对数字威胁，例如美国对手利用社交媒体煽动不和或抹黑候选人。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824021?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">众议员吉姆·乔丹去年要求 Meta 交出有关其内容审核决定的内部文件。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Julia Nikhinson – CNP/ZUMA Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>为什么共和党人现在把目标瞄准扎克伯格？</h3><p>共和党人表示，他们有证据表明 Facebook 和拜登政府合作审查美国人的言论，特别是在涉及 Covid-19 的讨论时。</p><p>路易斯安那州和密苏里州共和党总检察长在诉讼中发布的电子邮件显示，在拜登执政初期， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gop-led-house-to-probe-alleged-white-house-collusion-with-tech-giants-11673359215?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">白宫官员积极向 Facebook 施压</a>，要求其更主动地删除有关 Covid-19 的内容。白宫表示，正在努力防止公共卫生紧急情况下虚假信息的传播。</p><p> 2022 年 2 月，Facebook 向疾病控制与预防中心发送了一份清单，其中包含 20 多项有关幼儿疫苗的声明。有些说法很奇怪，例如含有微芯片的疫苗。其他人则处理更复杂的问题，例如“声称通过接种 Covid-19 来增强免疫力比接种疫苗更安全”。</p><p> “我们希望疾病预防控制中心能够确认这些说法是否也是虚假和有害的，”一名 Facebook 员工在一封电子邮件中写道。几周后，疾病预防控制中心做出了简短回应，宣布所有说法都是错误的，只有一个例外。 “哇，这太棒了，”一名 Facebook 员工回应道。 “我们现在将采取行动，以便能够删除除这一声明之外的所有声明。”</p><p>共和党人认为，这种互动最终会审查有关新冠政策的合法辩论，他们想更多地了解 Meta 的反应。</p><h3>民主党有何回应？</h3><p>司法委员会最高民主党人、纽约州民主党众议员杰罗德·纳德勒在一份声明中表示，乔丹的调查本身就是为了胁迫社交媒体公司改变内容审核政策。</p><p>他表示：“这是一种噱头，旨在恐吓那些在 2024 年选举前进行合理内容审核并提高人们对网络虚假信息认识的公司、大学和政府机构<strong>。</strong> ”纳德勒指的是<strong>&nbsp;</strong> to the Meta probe as well as Republicans&#39; investigation of some academic researchers who have documented the spread of what they considered potentially harmful information.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think there are grounds to hold Mark Zuckerberg in contempt of Congress?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> More broadly, Democrats reject the idea that social-media companies target conservatives, noting that many on the right have massive online followings. If anything, Democrats say, the companies have been too lax in removing harmful content, such as calls to riot at the US Capitol on Jan. 6, 2021.</p><p> Democrats also note that Republican administrations aren&#39;t immune to leaning on tech companies. In a House Oversight Committee hearing this past February, a former Twitter employee testified that the Trump White House had repeatedly asked the company to take down content related to the former president.</p><p> Meta, for its part, says its content-moderation decisions are independent, and not made with regard to politics.</p><p> Write to Ryan Tracy at <a href="mailto:ryan.tracy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.tracy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 17:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-zuckerberg-could-be-held-in-contempt-of-congress-what-to-know-e4027c45</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-zuckerberg-could-be-held-in-contempt-of-congress-what-to-know-e4027c45<author><![CDATA[Ryan Tracy]]></author><category>市场研究/公共关系</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>管理</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Senior Level Management</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>审查制度</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Human Rights/Civil Liberties</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Meta Platforms</category><category>梅塔</category><category>马克·扎克伯格</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>管理</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>senior level management</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>censorship</category><category> society</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>市场调查</category><category>公共关系</category><category>广告</category><category>marketing</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Startup Making It Easier for Young People to Put Money on Sports]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> PrizePicks says it offers fantasy-sports games, not gambling. Rivals disagree. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082512"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822911?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> PrizePicks app users put money down on predictions of how individual athletes will perform in games.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001082512"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/katherine-sayre" itemprop="url" rel="author">Katherine Sayre</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 27, 2023 10:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-startup-making-it-easier-for-young-people-to-put-money-on-sports-85422440"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Jackson Smith wanted to bet on sports as soon as he turned 18 and legally became an adult.</p><p> A basketball fan, Smith was blocked from using <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DKNG" class="company-name">DraftKings</a> and FanDuel apps because sports betting isn&#39;t legal in his home state of Minnesota. Then he heard about PrizePicks, an app where players put money down on predictions of how individual athletes will perform in games, such as the number of points scored or strikeouts recorded.</p><p> It billed itself as a daily fantasy-sports game, but it felt a lot like betting, and was legal in the state. He is now a frequent user.</p><p> With the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sports-better-win-lose-ddcaae24?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">surge of sports betting</a> in the US, a crop of new companies like PrizePicks are capitalizing on the demand, offering a sports-betting-like experience that falls outside of gambling laws. The tactic has drawn throngs of new users, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gambling-operators-push-sports-betting-at-collegesbut-not-to-students-they-say-11669815758?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">including young adults</a> and people who live in states where sports betting isn&#39;t legal.</p><p> Atlanta-based PrizePicks, which has attracted new users at a fast clip over the past year, says it offers fantasy-sports games, not gambling, and that it only operates in states where its products are legal.</p><p> Over the past year, the PrizePicks app has been downloaded more than the sports-gambling apps for Barstool Sports and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CZR" class="">Caesars Entertainment</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> and it has been gaining ground on the top two competitors in sports betting, FanDuel and DraftKings, according to estimates by data tracker Apptopia. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="780" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/64b76dae-b2cb-472f-bc2d-123469834df8-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> PrizePicks said in September of last year that it had paid out $500 million in prizes since it was launched in 2017. PrizePicks, which is a private company, declined to release its annual revenue.</p><p> The company&#39;s ascent has contributed to growing tension in the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gambling-revenues-hit-record-60-billion-last-year-9db4ed?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fast-evolving US sports-betting industry</a> , where fantasy apps and gambling companies are pursuing sports enthusiasts who are new to betting. Fantasy-sports apps are increasingly making products that are similar to sports betting, but are more lightly regulated.</p><p> Fantasy sports have largely been considered by states to be a game of skill, requiring research and knowledge to be competitive. Sports betting is considered gambling as a game of chance.</p><p> Gambling is regulated state-by-state, with different rules governing sports betting and fantasy sports; some states haven&#39;t regulated fantasy sports at all.</p><p> For many consumers, there is no distinction between the two.</p><p> “I have a bunch of college friends, and they all sports-bet,” Smith said. “I could ask 100 of them, &#39;What app do you guys use?&#39; Ninety-nine would say PrizePicks,” said the now-20-year-old, who attends the University of Wisconsin.</p><p> Some gambling regulators and rival companies say that PrizePicks&#39; model is making sports betting available to a younger audience, as well as in states where it hasn&#39;t been legalized or regulated with consumer protections. In most states, sports betting has a minimum age of 21, while daily fantasy-sports games typically have a minimum age of 18. PrizePicks, which in March raised its minimum age to 19, said it made the change to keep high-schoolers from playing.</p><p> PrizePicks has built an avid fandom for its simple “pick &#39;em” style games focused on individual athletes. Customers build what PrizePicks calls an entry by predicting how several athletes from different teams will perform in a game. The prediction is whether each player will exceed or miss a benchmark set by the company, such as whether a basketball player will score more or fewer than 25 points in a game. The winning cash payout is known as a prize.</p><p> It is similar to sports-betting-app offers in which gamblers make several bets on how players will perform, in what is known as a parlay. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824245?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> On a recent day, a PrizePicks player could make a $20 entry for a potential $100 payout on whether three Major League Baseball pitchers would get more than a certain number of strikeouts. On DraftKings&#39; sports-betting app, a $20 bet on the same scenario had a $107 payout.</p><p> “There are companies today posing as fantasy-sports operators, and they are running illegal sportsbooks,” Cesar Fernandez, FanDuel&#39;s head of state-government relations said at a recent conference of lawmakers from states with legalized gambling.</p><p> Jason Barclay, PrizePicks&#39; chief legal officer, said the company has “no interest in being a sportsbook” and that sports-betting companies can offer many wagers that PrizePicks can&#39;t as a fantasy company, such as the outcome or score of a single game or a single team.</p><p> The average age of PrizePicks&#39; customers has been 28, and moved closer to 29 after the minimum age was increased, the company said.</p><p> PrizePicks said its major driver of new customers has been referrals from existing customers. The company has marketing deals with National Football League team the Atlanta Falcons, Major League Soccer team Atlanta United and Nascar.</p><p> Critics of PrizePicks say that offering users the ability to put money down on <strong>&nbsp;</strong> the likelihood of athlete actions versus having users compete against other fans puts its products in the realm of gambling.</p><p> Maryland and West Virginia gambling regulators last year told PrizePicks to stop operating in those states because it was offering sports wagering without a sports-betting license.</p><p> John Myers, director of the West Virginia Lottery, which oversees sports betting in the state, issued a cease-and-desist letter to the company in January 2022, according to a copy of the letter viewed by The Wall Street Journal. A lottery spokeswoman declined to comment.</p><p> “The product offerings of PrizePicks described herein are not games of skill,” Myers said in the letter. “Rather, they are games of chance.”</p><p> PrizePicks shut down operations in Maryland and West Virginia. The company said the two states are outliers and that its fantasy contests are approved “by the vast majority of regulators in states that license and regulate daily fantasy sports.”</p><p> PrizePicks operates in 31 states and the District of Columbia, including in states such as California, Georgia and Texas, where sports-betting initiatives have failed. FanDuel operates online sports betting in 19 states, while DraftKings offers its sports-wagering app in 21 states.</p><p> “PrizePicks is the closest legal alternative to sports betting for the vast majority of North Americans,” the company says on its website.</p><p> PrizePicks co-founder and Chief Executive Adam Wexler said the company is focused on becoming a social platform for sports fans to engage with each other during events.</p><p> “We want to see our customers win, but you have to make skillful predictions,” Wexler said.</p><p> DraftKings and FanDuel successfully lobbied in the mid-2010s—before the broad legalization of sports betting—to have daily fantasy sports largely considered a game of skill.</p><p> Matt Schuler, executive director of the Ohio Casino Control Commission, said single-player fantasy games offered by companies like PrizePicks are allowing players to bet against the house as in gambling, rather than competing against other players as they do in daily fantasy games. PrizePicks doesn&#39;t operate in the state.</p><p> His office has sent letters to five other companies with similar concerns about their products. Schuler said companies are acting irresponsibly by offering a sports-betting product to people under 21 without labeling it gambling.</p><p> “This counterfeit version of sports gaming masquerading as a fantasy concept is going to become a problem,” Schuler said.</p><p> Write to Katherine Sayre at <a href="mailto:katherine.sayre@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">katherine.sayre@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/e1ce3c6a-4189-4884-b86b-4f96843a70c9.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-startup-making-it-easier-for-young-people-to-put-money-on-sports-85422440</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-startup-making-it-easier-for-young-people-to-put-money-on-sports-85422440<author><![CDATA[Katherine Sayre]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>游戏</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>选秀王</category><category>DKNG</category><category>凯撒娱乐</category><category>捷克共和国</category><category>Cesar Fernandez</category><category> Jason Barclay</category><category> Adam Wexler</category><category>游戏</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e exclusion filter</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Bud Light Brewer Lays Off Hundreds of U.S. Workers]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Anheuser-Busch restructures corporate offices amid controversy and sales slump <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088564"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="524" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824645?width=700&amp;height=524" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bud Light sales have tanked since April amid a backlash over a promotion with a transgender influencer.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jakub Porzycki/NurPhoto/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088564"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ngai-yeung" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ngai Yeung</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 27, 2023 9:04 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bud-light-brewer-lays-off-hundreds-of-u-s-workers-4cddf7d6"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BUD" class="company-name">Anheuser-Busch InBev</a> laid off hundreds of workers at its US offices after months of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bud-light-boycott-sales-dylan-mulvaney-6c23bb86?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">slumping sales at Bud Light</a> .</p><p> The world&#39;s largest brewer, which also sells Stella Artois and Budweiser, on Wednesday said the cuts would affect less than 2% of its roughly 18,000 US workforce. The layoffs won&#39;t impact front-line workers such as brewery and warehouse staff, the company said.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “While we never take these decisions lightly, we want to ensure that our organization continues to be set for future long-term success,” Anheuser-Busch Chief Executive Brendan Whitworth said in a written statement. “These corporate structure changes will enable our teams to focus on what we do best—brewing great beer for everyone.”</p><p> The restructuring eliminated corporate and marketing roles at major US offices, including St. Louis, New York and Los Angeles.</p><p> Bud Light sales have tanked since April amid a commercial <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-bud-light-handled-an-uproar-over-a-promotion-with-a-transgender-advocate-e457d5c6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">backlash over a promotion</a> with transgender influencer Dylan Mulvaney. Earlier this summer, Mexican brand Modelo Especial <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-modelo-dethroned-bud-light-as-americas-top-beer-f7cec085?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">dethroned</a> Bud Light as the top-selling beer in the US </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=E34005B0-8CAA-4A67-BE64-30DF4DA1DC75&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fbud-light-brewer-lays-off-hundreds-of-u-s-workers-4cddf7d6&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Dylan Mulvaney, a transgender influencer with more than 1.8 million Instagram followers, criticized Bud Light on Thursday for not publicly supporting her after her association with the beer brand sparked calls for a boycott. Photo: Angela Weiss/AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>AB InBev is slated to update investors on its latest quarterly financial results next week.</p><p> Write to Ngai Yeung at <a href="mailto:ngai.yeung@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ngai.yeung@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 13:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bud-light-brewer-lays-off-hundreds-of-us-workers-4cddf7d6</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/bud-light-brewer-lays-off-hundreds-of-us-workers-4cddf7d6<author><![CDATA[Ngai Yeung]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>机动车零件</category><category>Food/Beverages</category><category> Brewing</category><category> Alcoholic Beverages/Drinks</category><category>汽车</category><category>Beverages/Drinks</category><category>消费品</category><category>企业战略/规划</category><category>Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>企业组织架构重组</category><category>Lay-offs/Redundancies</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Anheuser-Busch InBev SA</category><category> ABI.BT</category><category>芽</category><category>BE:ABI</category><category>企业战略</category><category>planning</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业组织架构调整</category><category>裁员</category><category>裁员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>motor vehicle parts</category><category>食物</category><category>饮料</category><category>酿造</category><category>含酒精的饮料</category><category>饮料</category><category>汽车</category><category>消费品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why Elon Musk’s Plan for a Super App Won’t Be Easy in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The X owner has set an ambitious deadline for allowing users to &#39;conduct your entire financial world&#39; on the platform <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824614/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> PHOTO ILLUSTRATION: Bea Oyster/The Wall Street Journal; PHOTOS: iStock, Getty (2), Zuma Press <span>PHOTO ILLUSTRATION: Bea Oyster/The Wall Street Journal; PHOTOS: iStock, Getty (2), Zuma Press</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087896"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087896"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alexa-corse" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alexa Corse</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/meghan-bobrowsky" itemprop="url" rel="author">Meghan Bobrowsky</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/peter-rudegeair" itemprop="url" rel="author">Peter Rudegeair</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 27, 2023 9:02 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-elon-musks-plan-to-build-a-super-app-wont-be-easy-75f00930"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk</a> has waxed poetic about turning X, the social-media platform <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-says-twitter-will-change-its-logo-to-x-5f73c349?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">formerly known as Twitter,</a> into an “everything app,” capable of handling massive financial operations for users, and this week, he set an ambitious deadline.</p><p> “In the months to come, we will add comprehensive communications and the ability to conduct your entire financial world,” Musk <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1683656350046232578?s=20" target="_blank" class="icon none">tweeted</a> Monday evening.</p><p> While the idea of a super app is appealing to companies that want more ways to make money and grow their user base, it is easier said than done—even on a yearslong timeline. No app in the US has been able to successfully become a super app, though <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/super-app-musk-spiegel-dorsey-11657306485?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">many companies have talked about it</a> , including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PYPL" class="">PayPal</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> Snap and Twitter co-founder Jack Dorsey&#39;s Block. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0F91130A-ED9D-497B-A282-F26CCCF5DD91&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwhy-elon-musks-plan-to-build-a-super-app-wont-be-easy-75f00930&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Twitter&#39;s signature blue bird logo switched to an “X” for many users Monday after the platform&#39;s owner, Elon Musk, made the announcement in a series of tweets.这一变化是在 Twitter 品牌重塑之际发生的。照片：阿兰·乔卡德/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The story is different in Asia, where Chinese internet giant Tencent&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="company-name">WeChat</a> app is considered the archetypal super app and is used for everything from ride-hailing and e-commerce to mobile payments and even government services.</p><p> X didn&#39;t comment.</p><p> Theories vary on why a super app hasn&#39;t taken off in the West. One is that by the time the concept became popular in Asia, Western consumers were already accustomed to using a slate of different apps and websites, said Yory Wurmser, principal analyst at research firm Insider Intelligence. Credit cards also were more widespread in the West, which made a mobile payment service less necessary, he said.</p><p> That made it tougher to change users&#39; behavior. “You&#39;re not adding a huge amount of convenience by tacking all these different things onto one platform,” Wurmser said.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Will Elon Musk be successful in building a super app?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “WeChat arose in a country that was digitizing for the first time, almost exclusively via the smartphone, which meant no incumbent competition from traditional websites, banking rails like credit cards, or alternative social networks,” wrote analyst Ben Thompson, who writes the Stratechery newsletter. “Twitter/X exists in a particular context that makes the WeChat idea inaccessible to anyone, much less a company that has to expend the limited resources it still has just to keep the lights on.”</p><p> Another challenge is that getting into financial services means Musk&#39;s company will have to contend with far more regulation than it ever faced for moderating content. Companies that lend or move money are subject to oversight from a number of state and federal agencies, and they face penalties for not complying with rules around preventing money laundering and reimbursing users for the cost of fraud.</p><p> Over the past several months, Twitter has been applying for licenses in US states to operate as a money transmitter, according to regulators and people familiar with the matter. Those licenses would allow the platform to store and transfer money for users. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="446" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824643?width=700&amp;height=446" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chinese internet giant Tencent&#39;s WeChat app is considered the archetypal super app.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> So far the company has obtained licenses in at least four states, according to the Nationwide Multistate Licensing System, a registrar of nondepository financial services: Arizona, Michigan, Missouri and New Hampshire. While it is a start, getting licensed across the US can take up to a year or more, industry veterans said.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/twitter-tesla-neuralink-spacex-the-week-that-ran-on-elon-musk-time-11670159508?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Musk has a history</a> of setting ambitious deadlines, but ultimately emphasizing his bigger vision more than any specific date. His car company Tesla, for example, last year began delivering <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-set-to-deliver-semi-truck-to-pepsico-expanding-beyond-passenger-vehicles-11669899360?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a promised electric truck</a> —three years after Musk initially said it would arrive.</p><p> X isn&#39;t the first social-media company to try venturing into payments.</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a> parent Meta Platforms offers Meta Pay, a way to send and receive money via its messaging app and pay for goods online.<p></p><p> Some more ambitious projects have foundered. In 2019, Facebook unveiled a cryptocurrency project called Libra, later renamed Diem, that it pitched as a way for the social network&#39;s billions of users, even those without bank accounts, to easily pay for online purchases and transfer money. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824644?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tesla&#39;s electric semitrailer trucks, originally due out in 2019, began being delivered last year.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Benjamin Fanjoy/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> It never took off. Regulators around the world fretted that it could be misused by money launderers and terrorist financiers. Lawmakers called <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">Mark Zuckerberg</a> to testify about why Facebook should be trusted with users&#39; money. The project <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facebooks-cryptocurrency-venture-to-wind-down-sell-assets-11643248799?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was wound down</a> in early 2022.</p><p> “Moving money in and out of countries is more painful than you would expect,” said Morgan Beller, a former Facebook employee who co-founded Libra. Meta declined to comment for this article.</p><p> Beller said X could have a shot because Musk tends to run the company like a startup, despite it being an established platform with hundreds of millions of users.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “It&#39;s being run by a cowboy who&#39;s going to ask for forgiveness, not permission,” said Beller, who now works as a general partner at venture-capital firm NFX.</p><p> Snap, the company behind the popular social-media app <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SNAP" class="">Snapchat</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> also toyed with the idea of payments on its platform. In 2014, the app launched Snapcash—a way for users to send money to their friends—in partnership with the mobile-payment company now known as Block. Snap shut down the feature four years later.</p><p> PayPal set out in early 2021 to expand its digital wallet into a super app that would combine in-store and online payments, shopping tools and other consumer financial services, like savings accounts and stock trading. That goal partially motivated its interest in a potential acquisition of social-media platform <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PINS" class="">Pinterest</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p> But PayPal struggled to execute on its strategy. It <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/paypal-says-not-pursuing-acquisition-of-pinterest-11635148490?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">abandoned the Pinterest deal</a> after investors revolted, and to cut costs, it mothballed plans to offer stock trading and deprioritized in-store payments through its app.</p><p> Twitter had explored some payment features before Musk&#39;s takeover. In 2021, the company rolled out a tipping feature that directs users to third-party services, like PayPal&#39;s Venmo and Block&#39;s Cash App, to send and receive money.</p><p> Musk will have to convince users that the place where they post memes is a safe place to store their cash.</p><p> “Can I trust that when I move this money, is it going to go where I send it?” said James Wester, co-head of payments research at Javelin Strategy &amp; Research. “That is a question that needs to be answered for consumers.”</p><p> Write to Alexa Corse at <a href="mailto:alexa.corse@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alexa.corse@wsj.com</a> , Meghan Bobrowsky at <a href="mailto:meghan.bobrowsky@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">meghan.bobrowsky@wsj.com</a> and Peter Rudegeair at <a href="mailto:peter.rudegeair@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">peter.rudegeair@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e1f7a12e-412d-41e7-b6c1-3f6c0615c7c1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 13:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-elon-musks-plan-to-build-a-super-app-wont-be-easy-75f00930</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-elon-musks-plan-to-build-a-super-app-wont-be-easy-75f00930<author><![CDATA[Alexa CorseMeghan BobrowskyPeter Rudegeair]]></author><category> wsjfinance-ws</category><category> wsjfinance</category><category> WSJ公司</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>计算</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>Mobile Applications Software</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Snap</category><category> SNAP</category><category> Snapchat</category><category> Elon Musk</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人技术</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>计算</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>mobile applications software</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Microsoft Faces Mounting Scrutiny Over China-Linked Email Hack]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Leading lawmaker accuses tech company of security negligence that enabled spying campaign <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088740"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824608?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Microsoft says hackers got to the emails by first gaining access to an obscure but critical part of its infrastructure called an MSA digital signing key.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jacob Kepler for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001088740"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dustin-volz" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dustin Volz</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/robert-mcmillan" itemprop="url" rel="author">Robert McMillan</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 27, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-faces-mounting-scrutiny-over-china-linked-email-hack-7a028523"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MSFT" class="company-name">Microsoft</a> is attracting renewed scrutiny and accusations of negligent security over a hack that allowed China to spy on top Biden administration officials, as some security researchers say the breach may be worse than initially suspected.</p><p> The Chinese hack, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-government-emails-hacked-in-suspected-chinese-espionage-campaign-f4fa8de6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">disclosed earlier this month</a> , compromised the unclassified Microsoft email inboxes of senior State Department officials, including the US ambassador to China, as well as Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo and others, according to US officials.</p><p> Full details about the attack, including how it began, aren&#39;t publicly known, but it has prompted a number of congressional inquiries. On Thursday a leading lawmaker on cybersecurity issues, Sen. Ron Wyden (D-Ore.), asked for three separate federal probes of Microsoft&#39;s “negligent cybersecurity practices” that he said enabled a Chinese espionage campaign against the US government.</p><p> “Even with the limited details that have been made public so far, Microsoft bears significant responsibility for this new incident,” Wyden said in the letter, which is addressed to Attorney General Merrick Garland, Federal Trade Commission Chair Lina Khan and Jen Easterly, the director of the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency.</p><p> Microsoft said the hackers obtained access to an obscure but critical part of its infrastructure called an MSA digital signing key, which was then used to gain access to customer data. The company has explained aspects of the hack in blog posts but said how it unfolded is currently unknown. The tech company also said it would make certain tools that can help spot cyberattacks free, after its tiered payment system for those services <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-to-offer-some-cybersecurity-tools-free-after-suspected-china-hack-6db94221?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">drew criticism following the hack</a> .</p><p> A Microsoft spokesman said that the company is working with government agencies and is committed to sharing information about the hack. “This incident demonstrates the evolving challenges of cybersecurity in the face of sophisticated attacks,” he said.</p><p> “These signing keys are the most precious secret that you have,” said Ami Luttwak, co-founder of the cloud-security company Wiz, in an interview. “It&#39;s like you have a printing machine to all of the passports in the world: You can become anyone that you want.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824686?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The US says the hack compromised the unclassified Microsoft email inboxes of officials including Commerce Secretary Gina Raimondo.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：内森霍华德/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Researchers at Wiz said that the digital key that was obtained had been issued in 2016 and wasn&#39;t taken out of service until a few weeks after the attack was discovered.</p><p> The Microsoft spokesman said the Wiz findings presented “hypothetical attack scenarios” that the company hasn&#39;t observed.</p><p> MSA keys can be used to gain access to Microsoft&#39;s consumer products, but because of a flaw in Microsoft&#39;s cloud, the hackers were able to use the stolen key to access government and corporate accounts, according to Microsoft.</p><p> Security experts and Wyden questioned several Microsoft practices, including apparently allowing the same MSA key to be used for years.</p><p> “Federal cybersecurity guidelines, industry best practices, and Microsoft&#39;s own recommendations to customers, dictate that encryption keys be refreshed more frequently, for the very reason that they might become compromised,” Wyden said.</p><p> Digital certificates also played a role in Russia&#39;s SolarWinds hack, discovered in 2020. Wyden also faulted Microsoft for its role in that incident.</p><p> Although experts praised Microsoft for providing some details about the Chinese hack, some have called for more disclosure, saying it is needed to determine the extent of the damage and whether it could happen again.</p><p> “My concern here is that we don&#39;t know how the key got away,” said Karim El-Melhaoui,</p> principal security architect with security company O3 Cyber.<p></p><p> In his letter, reviewed by the Journal, Wyden asked the Justice Department to investigate whether Microsoft violated federal law relating to cybersecurity standards for government contractors. He also asked the FTC to investigate Microsoft&#39;s privacy and data-security practices, including whether the alleged security lapses at issue in the hack began before the expiration in December of a 20-year consent decree the agency imposed following an earlier security incident.</p><p> Finally, the senator asked the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-forms-cybersecurity-review-board-to-probe-failures-11643898601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Cyber Safety Review Board</a> to review the cyber-espionage campaign and why Microsoft&#39;s apparent security shortfalls weren&#39;t previously discovered by government audits.</p><p> “Holding Microsoft responsible for its negligence will require a whole-of-government effort,” Wyden said.</p><p> The letter is the latest effort by lawmakers and cybersecurity experts to gain a fuller understanding of the hack, allegedly state-sponsored. US officials have sought to play it down as routine espionage between adversarial nations.</p><p> Some cybersecurity specialists have deemed it an unusually powerful and impressive compromise of Microsoft&#39;s cloud-based email infrastructure. A separate bipartisan letter signed by 14 senators, sent Wednesday and earlier reported by Newsweek, asked the State Department&#39;s chief information officer for an unclassified briefing on the hack by early September.</p><p> Wiz believes that the hackers could have been able to steal data in addition to emails, such as Microsoft Teams chat messages and SharePoint documents.</p><p> The US hasn&#39;t formally linked the attack to China, though Microsoft attributed it to a Chinese hacking group and officials and lawmakers have said Beijing is responsible. China has denied the allegations.</p><p> More than two dozen organizations globally were affected, Microsoft said. Fewer than 10 organizations were compromised in the US, with the hackers apparently accessing a small number of individual email accounts in each case, US officials have said. They have described the attack as narrowly targeted at individuals whose communications were believed to possess high intelligence value.</p><p> Write to Dustin Volz at <a href="mailto:dustin.volz@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dustin.volz@wsj.com</a> and Robert McMillan at <a href="mailto:robert.mcmillan@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">robert.mcmillan@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-faces-mounting-scrutiny-over-china-linked-email-hack-7a028523</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/microsoft-faces-mounting-scrutiny-over-china-linked-email-hack-7a028523<author><![CDATA[Dustin VolzRobert McMillan]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>专有的</category><category>计算机/消费电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>计算</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>信息技术</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Privacy Issues/Information Security</category><category> Cybercrime/Hacking</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>微软</category><category>微软公司</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>信息技术</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>隐私问题</category><category>信息安全</category><category>网络犯罪</category><category>黑客攻击</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>电脑</category><category>消费类电子产品</category><category>软件</category><category>应用软件</category><category>计算</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[What Happens When You Stop at One Glass of Wine a Day?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Our wine columnist gave it her best shot, in accordance with government-issued dietary guidelines. She was surprised by the results—and her own doctor&#39;s opinion. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060700"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="655" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822859?width=860&amp;height=655" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> SMALL DOSES One glass of wine per day means exactly that.根据政府的指导方针，你不能在第三天节省你的分配和挥霍。</p><p class="imageCredit"> Illustration: Mitch Blunt </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060700"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lettie-teague"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS873_TEAGUE_A_20180913112322.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lettie-teague" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lettie Teague</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 27, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-glass-of-wine-a-day-64ead6a9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <strong>READING THE MOST</strong> recent Dietary Guidelines for Americans from the US Department of Agriculture and US Department of Health and Human Services, I found that women are advised to drink one glass of wine or less and men two glasses or less daily.许多人遵循这个建议吗？</p><p> I actually did, at least for a while. Ordinarily, I drink more than one glass a day—usually two. And when I took a casual poll of friends and acquaintances, I found that I&#39;m far from alone in exceeding government guidelines. Very few said that they stop at a single daily glass; some drink more than I do.</p><p> What if I downscaled my drinking, at least for a week? What short-term benefits might there be? I decided to give it a try.</p><p> The 2020-2025 guidelines cover a wide range of topics related to food and drink and contain extensive nutritional advice. For example, the guidelines suggest that around 85% of one&#39;s calories should come from “nutrient dense” choices like fruits, vegetables and grains, leaving the remaining 15% for “other uses.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> What if I downscaled my drinking, at least for a week? What  short-term benefits might there be? <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p> Alcohol ranks among those other uses, and the advice regarding its consumption is especially stern. Consider, for example: “Evidence indicates that, among those who drink, higher average alcohol consumption is associated with an increased risk of death from all causes compared with lower average alcohol consumption.” The list of conditions that might occur as a result of excess alcohol consumption is quite long—and quite sobering. I&#39;ll spare you the specifics here.</p><p> I was disappointed to find that the government&#39;s proposed one glass is a stingy 5-ounce pour of 12% alcohol wine. If I got five ounces for a $25 glass of wine in a restaurant or bar I&#39;d be tempted to object. Six ounces is generally considered the industry standard; a few restaurants I know even pour a bit more.</p><p> Furthermore, most white wines these days exceed the government&#39;s 12% figure, and it&#39;s increasingly hard to find any red wine that isn&#39;t at least 14% alcohol or more. (Warmer weather means riper grapes, which produce higher alcohol wines.)</p><p> A 5-ounce glass of 12% alcohol wine has about 120 calories, according to the guidelines. And lest you consider forgoing that one glass a day to drink two glasses the next, the guidelines discourage that: The one drink or less a day for women and two for men, they stipulate, is “not intended as an average over several days, but rather the amount consumed on any single day.”</p><p> While I didn&#39;t save up my wine allotment for a few days to have three glasses the third day, I did deviate ever so slightly from the official guidelines. I drank a six- not 5-ounce serving. And the wines I drank almost always exceeded that 12% alcohol figure. I like lower-alcohol wines, but they&#39;re elusive and I didn&#39;t necessarily want to drink a low-alcohol Muscadet or Vinho Verde or Lambrusco for several days in a row. I wanted something a bit richer and more complex.</p><p> After all, since my husband rarely drinks more than one glass at any time, once I opened the bottle, we would both have to drink the same wine for several days. That meant I had to consider the closure, too: Screwcap bottles stay fresher longer.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How many glasses of wine do you drink each day?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Additionally, there was the question of timing. When did I want to drink my one glass? I didn&#39;t want to drink too much (or perhaps any) of the wine before dinner because I&#39;d have nothing left by the end or maybe even the middle of the meal. Drinking my one glass of wine very slowly, however, could be a positive development: Perhaps I&#39;d savor the wine even more. Or would I merely be eking out tiny moments of pleasure until I reached the too-soon end? And with a white, I found that the wine grew tepid over the time it took me to drink it.</p><p> With so much on my mind, I found after a few days that I was not only drinking less but also eating less food. Then came the challenge of eating out. A few days into my one-glass regimen we met friends for dinner at our favorite BYO, Divina Ristorante in Caldwell, NJ</p><p> How would I be able to measure just one serving of the very good 2021 Bruno Giacosa Roero Arneis (a white wine from Piedmont, Italy) that I&#39;d brought along? Chef Mario Carlino provided a measuring cup.</p><p> Drinking only one glass proved economical, as one bottle was enough for our table of four. Our friend Bobby, like my husband, doesn&#39;t drink much at all. He, in fact, had been the only one of my friends who didn&#39;t recoil when I&#39;d announced I would be drinking just one glass. My friend Burt said he could drink only one glass of wine “as long as I have a Martini beforehand,” while my friends Robert and Tom adamantly dismissed the idea. “One glass! Never!” they declared, nearly in unison. “Not even for brunch,” said Tom. “Your first glass sets you up, mellows you, and then you have a glass of wine with dinner,” Robert added. “Your third glass could be dessert,” Tom suggested.</p><p> At the end of my one-glass week I noticed a few clear benefits. I&#39;d lost a couple pounds and I was sleeping better, too. And yet, despite such positive developments, when the week was up I happily went back to drinking that second glass (and another half-glass on my first day back to my normal routine, to celebrate). I&#39;d missed the sense of expansiveness, of total relaxation that comes with sitting down to a meal that begins with a glass of wine and extends to another that I don&#39;t have to carefully parcel out. My husband even drank a second glass with me. Maybe I will go back to drinking one glass of wine with dinner from time to time. But not right now.</p><p> A few weeks later, I had a checkup with my doctor, a top gastroenterologist in New York and a non-drinker. I told him about my one-glass-of-wine scheme and asked what he thought, fully expecting some sort of commendation. “You could drink up to half a bottle of wine a day,” he replied, “and be fine.”</p><p> <strong>Email Lettie at <a href="mailto:wine@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">wine@wsj.com</a> .</strong> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
